EDA - Pairwise Comparison¶

In [513]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,60))

# extract relevant column names (metrics)
var_list = data.columns[2:]
depn_var = data.iloc[:,-1].values
for n in range(1,len(var_list)):

    # generate figures for each metric on each device
    fig.add_subplot(len(var_list), 3, n)
    x_data = data[var_list[n-1]]
    ax = plt.scatter(x_data, depn_var)
    # Plots best fit line for scatter data
    ax = plt.plot(np.unique(x_data), np.poly1d(np.polyfit(x_data, depn_var, 1))(np.unique(x_data)), color = 'darkred')
    plt.title(var_list[n-1]+' vs '+ 'Price Change%', fontsize=15)
    plt.tight_layout()

It appears that TipRank's rating variable and LowPT/CurrPT, AvgPT/CurrPT, and HighPT/CurrPT. We can check Correlation Coefficient to see if these variables do indeed have the highest correlation with the Price Change %

In [510]:
import scipy.stats as stats

df_corr = pd.DataFrame()
pearson = []
spearman = []
feat = []
for i in range(2,len(data.values[0])-1):
    feat.append(data.columns[i])
    pearson.append(stats.pearsonr(data[data.columns[i]], data[data.columns[-1]])[0])
    spearman.append(stats.spearmanr(data[data.columns[i]], data[data.columns[-1]])[0])
df_corr['Feature Variable'] = feat
df_corr['Pearson-R'] = pearson
df_corr['Spearman-Rho'] = spearman

Another simple way to improve the model accuracy (high R^2 score) is to interact Zack's Rank and TipRank's Rating scores, if both sources give a high score to a specific stock, then most likely it will have a high potential for positive growth

As expected, the mean jumped slightly, but there are still too many feature variables that may not be necessary. Another processing step can be to do feature selection using backwards elimination of feature variables.

In [470]:
copy_xtrain = scaled_x_train.copy()
In [471]:
x_test = []
best_columns = []
max_score = 0
best_col = -1

# Backwards eliminate 3 columns first
for j in range(5):
    if best_col == old_best_col:
        break
    old_best_col = best_col
    for i in range(len(copy_xtrain[0])):
        
        new_table = np.delete(copy_xtrain, i, axis = 1)
        model = LinearRegression(n_jobs = -1)
        model.fit(new_table, y_train)
        scores = cross_val_score(model, new_table, y_train, scoring='r2', cv=5)
        curr_score = scores.mean()

        if curr_score > max_score:   
            best_col = i
            max_score = curr_score
    if best_col == old_best_col:
        continue
    else:
        copy_xtrain = np.delete(copy_xtrain, best_col, axis = 1)
        
        print('Column removed = ', best_col)

Conclusion¶

In the end, remember here that the data is not realistic since Q3 has not ended yet and it is actually better to use Q4 or 2021 Q1 price change% data as the dependent variable.


Garbage dataset will produce a garbage model. Nothing we do will be able to push the model to above 0.50 R^2 score if we are using September stock prices as the dependent variable in this dataset.


The goal for this demo is not to build the perfect regression model for the dataset collected.


The goal of this project however is just to show that webscraping and document sentiment analys can collect useful data for stock market long-term investment predictions.
